channel.title: NASA Image of the Day
channel.description: The latest NASA "Image of the Day" image.

item.title: Webb Reveals New Details in Pillars of Creation
item.description: Our James Webb Space Telescope has captured a new image of the famous Pillars of Creation—first imaged by the Hubble Space Telescope in 1995—that reveals new details about the region.

item.title: Lucy Spots Earth and Moon
item.description: On Oct. 13, 2022, NASA’s Lucy spacecraft captured this image of the Earth and the Moon from 890,000 miles (1.4 million km) away.

item.title: Mapping the Entire Night Sky
item.description: This mosaic is composed of images covering the entire sky, taken by the ​Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer (WISE) as part of WISE’s 2012 All-Sky Data Release.

item.title: Jupiter in Ganymede’s Shadow
item.description: During its 40th close pass by Jupiter, our Juno spacecraft saw Ganymede cast a large, dark spot on the planet on Feb. 25, 2022.

item.title: IXPE Measures Exploded Star Remains
item.description: When a massive star collapsed in the Cassiopeia constellation, it generated a supernova explosion with some of the fastest shockwaves in the Milky Way.

item.title: Hubble Views a Turbulent Stellar Nursery
item.description: The lives of newborn stars are tempestuous, as this image of the Herbig-Haro objects HH 1 and HH 2 from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope depicts.

item.title: Crew-4 Members Pose for Pre-Return Photo
item.description: NASA’s SpaceX Crew-4 members Jessica Watkins, Bob Hines, Kjell Lindgren, and Samantha Cristoforetti link arms for a portrait on Oct. 14, 2022, just before boarding the Dragon Freedom crew ship, undocking from the International Space Station, and returning to Earth, completing a 170-day space research mission.

item.title: Aerial Leaf Peeping in Adirondack Park
item.description: Our Operational Land Imager-2 on Landsat 9 acquired this vibrant image of deciduous trees and conifers in the Adirondack Mountains in northeast New York on Oct. 8, 2022.

item.title: Safe Return for NASA’s SpaceX Crew-4 Astronauts
item.description: After 170 days in orbit, NASA astronauts Bob Hines, Kjell Lindgren, and Jessica Watkins and European Space Agency astronaut Samantha Cristoforetti safely splashed down Friday, October 14, 2022, off the coast of Jacksonville, Florida, completing the agency’s fourth commercial crew mission to the International Space Station.

item.title: JPSS-2 Stacked Atop LOFTID Spacecraft
item.description: JPSS-2 Stacked Atop LOFTID Spacecraft.

item.title: Systems Engineer Andres Rivera
item.description: “A lot of people in similar positions as myself, we struggle a lot with confidence and imposter syndrome – I try to help people see that there’s an opportunity, and that if you work hard and are willing to evoke whatever it takes to get there, you can get it.” – Andres Rivera, Systems Engineer II, Europa Clipper, NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory

item.title: Greetings from the Cupola
item.description: Expedition 67 flight engineers Bob Hines and Jessica Watkins are all smiles in this Sept. 12, 2022, image from the International Space Station cupola.

item.title: Sun Rings in New Month with Strong Flare
item.description: The Sun released an X1 solar flare, captured by our Solar Dynamics Observatory (SDO) on Oct. 2, 2022.

item.title: Hubble Snaps a Pair of Interacting Galaxies
item.description: The two interacting galaxies making up the pair known as Arp-Madore 608-333 seem to float side by side in this image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope.

item.title: NASA’s SpaceX Crew-5 Mission Casts Long Exposure Light Beam
item.description: In this 20-second exposure from Oct. 5, 2022, a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket carrying the company's Crew Dragon spacecraft is launched on NASA’s SpaceX Crew-5 mission to the International Space Station (ISS).

item.title: Solid Science from Serena Auñón-Chancellor
item.description: Astronaut Serena Auñón-Chancellor installs samples for the Microgravity Investigation of Cement Solidification (MICS) experiment aboard the International Space Station (ISS) in this image from Nov. 27, 2018.

item.title: Astronaut Nicole Mann Trains in T-38
item.description: Astronaut Nicole Mann sits inside a T-38 trainer jet at Ellington Field in Houston, Texas in this image from Nov. 15, 2018.

item.title: Staring Into the Hurricane's Eye
item.description: On September 28, the Landsat 8 satellite passed directly over Ian’s eye as the storm approached southwest Florida. The natural-color image above was acquired by the Operational Land Imager (OLI) at 11:57 a.m. local time (15:57 Universal Time), three hours before the storm made landfall in Caya Costa.

item.title: DART’s Penultimate View
item.description: This is the last complete image of the asteroid Dimorphos, as seen by our Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART) 2 seconds before impact.

item.title: Neptune Shows Off Its Rings in Near-Infrared Light
item.description: On Sept. 21, 2022, the James Webb Space Telescope delivered the clearest view of Neptune’s rings in more than 30 years.

item.title: Ellen Ochoa Suits Up
item.description: Astronaut Ellen Ochoa, STS-110 flight engineer, wears a launch and entry suit as part of water survival training in the Neutral Buoyancy Laboratory in 2001.

item.title: DART Team Celebrates Successful Collision
item.description: In this image from Sept. 26, 2022, the Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART) team, Dr. Thomas Zurbuchen, and guests at Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory cheer as they receive confirmation of DART’s collision with Dimorphos.

item.title: Golden DART’s Galactic Unboxing
item.description: Technicians prepare to move NASA’s Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART) spacecraft from a shipping container onto a work stand inside the Astrotech Space Operations Facility at Vandenberg Space Force Base in California in this image from Oct. 4, 2021.

item.title: John W. Young’s Lunar Salute
item.description: Astronaut John W. Young, commander of the Apollo 16 lunar landing mission, leaps from the lunar surface as he salutes the United States flag at the Descartes landing site during the first Apollo 16 spacewalk.

item.title: Endeavour Gets a Piggyback Ride
item.description: Our Shuttle Carrier Aircraft ferries the Space Shuttle Endeavour over the Johnson Space Center in Houston in this Sept. 20, 2012, image.

item.title: Frank Rubio Trains for Spacewalk
item.description: In this March 7, 2022, image, astronaut Frank Rubio gets help putting on a spacesuit at the Neutral Buoyancy Laboratory at NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston to train for spacewalks.

item.title: A Stormy Stellar Nursery
item.description: This cloudy, turbulent scene shows a stellar nursery within the Large Magellanic Cloud known as N159.

item.title: Michael E. López-Alegría Poses During Spacewalk
item.description: Astronaut Michael E. López-Alegría, mission specialist, is photographed in this close-up view during one of the STS-92 sessions of extravehicular activity on Oct. 18, 2000.

item.title: A Bird's-Eye View of the Vehicle Assembly Base
item.description: A little blue heron is seen in front of the Vehicle Assembly Building as preparations for launch continue, Friday, Sept. 2, 2022, at NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

item.title: Hubble Studies a Spectacular Spiral
item.description: The galaxy NGC 1961 unfurls its gorgeous spiral arms in this newly released image from NASA’s Hubble Space Telescope.

item.title: Snowcapped Mountains in Western China
item.description: The International Space Station captured a portion of the Tanggula Mountains near Hala Lake from 260 miles above the Earth on Sept. 5th, 2022.

item.title: Setting the Clock on a Stellar Explosion
item.description: A new image of SNR 0519-69.0 shows the debris of a star that exploded several hundred years ago in Earth’s timeframe.

item.title: Reflecting on President Kennedy's Moonshot Speech
item.description: On Sept. 12, 1962, President Kennedy speaks before a crowd of 35,000 people at Rice University in Houston.

item.title: Mediterranean Cities Light Up the Night
item.description: This nighttime photograph from the International Space Station (ISS) as it orbited 261 miles above looks across the Mediterranean Sea from north Africa to southern Europe.

item.title: NASA's Hubble Finds Spiraling Stars, Providing Window into Early Universe
Voyager 1’s Mission to the Outer Planet Begins
item.description: The Voyager mission was designed to take advantage of a rare geometric arrangement of the outer planets in the late 1970s and the 1980s which allowed for a four-planet tour for a minimum of propellant and trip time.

item.title: A Cosmic Tarantula, Caught by NASA’s Webb
The Crater Farm
item.description: Three impact craters are displayed in this three-dimensional perspective view of the surface of Venus taken NASA's Magellan, the first deep space probe launched by a space shuttle.

item.title: Lacerta’s Star Outshines a Galaxy
item.description: A little-studied star, TYC 3203-450-1, upstages a galaxy in this Hubble Telescope image from December 2017.

item.title: A Peek Into Jupiter’s Inner Life
item.description: Auroras and hazes glow in this composite image of Jupiter taken by the James Webb Space Telescope's Near-Infrared Camera (NIRCam).

item.title: Early Morning Artemis I
item.description: NASA’s Space Launch System (SLS) rocket with the Orion spacecraft aboard is seen atop the mobile launcher at Launch Pad 39B, Monday, Aug. 29, 2022, as the Artemis I launch teams loaded more than 700,000 gallons of cryogenic propellants including liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen.

item.title: Apollo 15 Catches Earth on the Horizon
item.description: This view of the crescent Earth over the Moon's horizon was taken during the Apollo 15 lunar landing mission.

item.title: NASA T-38s Soar Over Artemis I
item.description: ​T-38 planes are a fixture of astronaut training, making pilots and mission specialists think quicky in changing situations.

item.title: Milky Way Time Lapse
item.description: This time lapse of the Milky Way Galaxy taken from the International Space Station (ISS) also captured a lightning strike on Earth so bright that it lights up the space station’s solar panels.

item.title: The Historic X-1E Looks Forward
item.description: The supersonic X-1E research aircraft was the last of NASA's experimental X-1 series of aircraft.

item.title: NASA's Europa Clipper in High Bay 1
item.description: The core of NASA’s Europa Clipper spacecraft has taken center stage in the Spacecraft Assembly Facility at the agency’s Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Southern California.

item.title: Moon Over New Orleans
item.description: A paddlewheeler makes its way up the Mississippi River as the moon rises over New Orleans on Sunday evening, Aug. 22, 2021.

item.title: Voyager 1 Sees the Great Red Spot
item.description: Launched in 1977, the twin Voyager probes are NASA’s longest-operating mission and the only spacecraft ever to explore interstellar space.

item.title: We Are Going: Artemis I on Launch Pad
item.description: NASA’s Space Launch System (SLS) rocket with the Orion spacecraft aboard is seen atop the mobile launcher as it is rolled up the ramp at Launch Pad 39B, Wednesday, Aug. 17, 2022, at NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida.

item.title: Perennial Perseids
item.description: The Perseid meteors are an annual event many skywatchers look forward to, as they often produce lots of shooting stars to enjoy.

item.title: Aquanaut Gets to Work Underwater
item.description: A team of roboticists from NASA’s Johnson Space Center in Houston have applied their expertise in making robots for deep space to designing a fully electric shape-changing submersible robot that will cut costs for maritime industries.

item.title: Hubble Peers at Celestial Cloudscape
item.description: This celestial cloudscape from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope captures the colorful region in the Orion Nebula surrounding the Herbig-Haro object HH 505.

item.title: Artemis I Moonikin Campos Inspection and Install
item.description: Artemis I Moonikin Campos Inspection and Install

item.title: NASA’s B377SGT Super Guppy Turbine Cargo Airplane lands at Moffett Field at NASA Ames
item.description: In this picture from 2016, our Super Guppy, a specialized aircraft with a unique hinged nose, lands at Moffett Field at NASA Ames.

item.title: Moon Mosaic
item.description: This Moon-mosaic is comprised of 1,231 images taken by the Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter's (LRO) Narrow-Angle Camera (NAC) in the summer of 2018.

item.title: Curiosity's Dusty Selfie
item.description: Since August 2012, Curiosity has been exploring 3-mile-high Mt. Sharp in Gale Crater. The rover has climbed more than 2,000 feet (612 meters), reaching progressively younger rocks that serve as a record on how Mars has evolved from a wet, habitable planet to a cold desert environment.

item.title: Hubble Gazes at a Star-Studded Skyfield
item.description: This star-studded image from the NASA/ESA Hubble Space Telescope shows the heart of the globular cluster NGC 6638 in the constellation Sagittarius.

item.title: Ice Stars
item.description: Like distant galaxies amid clouds of interstellar dust, chunks of sea ice drift through graceful swirls of grease ice in the frigid waters of Foxe Basin near Baffin Island in the Canadian Arctic.

item.title: Wildflowers in Bloom at Kennedy Space Center
item.description: With wildflowers surrounding the view, NASA’s Space Launch System Moon rocket – carried atop the crawler-transporter 2 – arrives at Launch Pad 39B at the agency’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida on June 6, 2022.

item.title: Webb Captures Stellar Gymnastics in The Cartwheel Galaxy
